<DocsLayout title="Getting Started with Streams" sidebar={streamsSidebar} description="Set up Streams in your Kotlin project">

<h1>Getting Started</h1>

<p class="text-xl text-gray-400 !mt-2 !mb-8">
  Add Streams to your project and create your first reactive values.
</p>

<h2>1. Add the dependency</h2>

<p>In your <code>build.gradle.kts</code>:</p>

<Code code={`dependencies {
    implementation("${dep.streams}")
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<p>Find the latest version on <a href={mavenCentralUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Maven Central</a>.</p>

    <p>Streams is a Kotlin Multiplatform library — it works in <code>commonMain</code>, <code>jvmMain</code>, <code>jsMain</code>,
        and <code>nativeMain</code> (linuxX64, linuxArm64, macosX64, macosArm64, mingwX64).</p>

<h2>2. Create a StreamSource</h2>

<p>A <code>StreamSource</code> is a mutable reactive value. It always has a current value.</p>

    <Code code={`import io.peekandpoke.ultra.streams.StreamSource

val counter = StreamSource(0)

// Read the current value
println(counter())  // 0

// Set a new value
counter(1)
println(counter())  // 1

// Modify based on current value
counter.modify { this + 1 }
println(counter())  // 2

// Reset to initial
counter.reset()
println(counter())  // 0`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<h2>3. Subscribe to changes</h2>

<p>Subscribing immediately delivers the current value, then every subsequent change:</p>

<Code code={`val name = StreamSource("Alice")

val unsubscribe = name.subscribeToStream { value ->
    println("Name is: ${'$'}value")
}
// prints "Name is: Alice" immediately

name("Bob")
// prints "Name is: Bob"

name("Charlie")
// prints "Name is: Charlie"

// Stop listening
unsubscribe()`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<h2>4. Transform with operators</h2>

<p>Operators create new read-only streams derived from a source:</p>

<Code code={`val source = StreamSource(5)

// map — transform each value
val doubled = source.map { it * 2 }
println(doubled())  // 10

// filter — only pass values matching a predicate
val big = source.filter(initial = 0) { it > 10 }
println(big())  // 0 (initial, since 5 doesn't match)

source(20)
println(big())     // 20
println(doubled()) // 40`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<h2>5. Combine streams</h2>

<p>Merge two streams into one:</p>

<Code code={`val a = StreamSource(1)
val b = StreamSource(10)

val sum = a.combinedWith(b) { x, y -> x + y }
println(sum())  // 11

a(5)
println(sum())  // 15

b(100)
println(sum())  // 105`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<h2>How subscriptions work</h2>

<p>Streams use <strong>lazy subscriptions</strong>. When you chain operators like <code>source.map { }.filter { }</code>, no work happens until someone subscribes to the end of the chain. The subscription propagates upstream — and when the last subscriber unsubscribes, the entire chain tears down.</p>

<p>This means unused streams cost nothing.</p>

    <Aside>Well, almost nothing. The objects exist in memory. But no callbacks fire, no upstream work happens.</Aside>

    <div class="not-prose mt-8 flex gap-4">
